     \


7. Go to sketch > Upload. The Arduino IDE will do some work then the Teensyduio window will pop up. It should automatically upload the code. If Arduino says this didn’t happen, press the small white button on the teensy. 

    

<p id="gdcalert4" ><span style="color: red; font-weight: bold">>>>>>  gd2md-html alert: inline image link here (to images/image4.jpg). Store image on your image server and adjust path/filename/extension if necessary. </span><br>(<a href="#">Back to top</a>)(<a href="#gdcalert5">Next alert</a>)<br><span style="color: red; font-weight: bold">>>>>> </span></p>


![alt_text](images/image4.jpg "image_tooltip")


8. The LED on the Teensy should be blinking much brighter now. Now lets get some of the code you downloaded onto the Teensy.  \
In that zip you got from the [class folder](https://drive.google.com/open?id=1ZmY5dxboq-nV-116lR2aDetTndwpMOzo), open up “Class_1_-_0_-_short_blink.ino” and upload it just like before. The LED should be making short, dim blinks again.  \
 \
Now you’re ready to learn how to use all this to make your own weird music/noise/art/??? Device!  \
